-- 
Benchmark DAX Index Declines After U.S. Jobless Claims, GDP Growth Data

-- B y   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 
2011-05-26T16:18:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-26/dax-index-little-changed-before-u-s-economic-growth-report-bayer-falls.html
German stocks retreated after U.S.
reports showed the country’s jobless claims unexpectedly climbed
last week and its economy grew more slowly in the first quarter
than economists had predicted.  Bayerische Motoren Werke AG (BMW)  and  Volkswagen AG (VOW)  led a retreat
in European carmakers, both falling by more than 1.5 percent.
 Bayer AG (BAYN)  slipped 1.9 percent as UBS AG scaled back its
recommendation on the maker of aspirin.  Singulus Technologies AG (SNG) 
jumped the most in more than a month after posting an outlook
for 2011.  The benchmark  DAX Index (DAX)  lost 0.8 percent to 7,114.09 at the
5:30 p.m. close in Frankfurt, the second decline this week. The
gauge has fallen 5.5 percent from this year’s high on May 2 as
 Fitch Ratings  cut Greece’s credit rating to B+,  Standard &
Poor’s  warned it may downgrade Italy’s debt and Spain’s ruling
party suffered its worst election defeat in 30 years. The
broader  HDAX Index (HDAX)  fell 0.7 percent today.  “A weak trend in economic data continues,” said Daniel Weston, a Munich-based portfolio adviser at Schroeder Equities
GmbH.  A report today showed the  U.S. economy  grew at a 1.8
percent annual rate in the first quarter. The increase in gross
domestic product matched the Commerce Department’s estimate of
last month and compared with a 3.1 percent gain in the prior
quarter, figures showed today in  Washington . The median forecast
of economists surveyed by Bloomberg News was for a 2.2 percent
increase.  U.S. Labor Report  A separate report from the U.S. Labor Department showed
jobless claims increased by 10,000 to 424,000 in the week ended
May 21. The median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News
survey was for a drop to 404,000.  German stocks extended declines after Luxembourg’s Jean-
Claude Juncker, who leads the group of euro-area finance
ministers, said the  International Monetary Fund  may not release
its portion of aid to  Greece  next month.  BMW, the world’s biggest manufacturer of luxury cars, slid
1.7 percent to 59.70 euros, while Volkswagen,  Europe ’s largest
carmaker, lost 1.9 percent to 121.75 euros. Carmakers posted the
second-worst performance among 19 industry groups in the
benchmark Stoxx Europe 600 Index.  Bayer fell 1.9 percent to 54.71 euros after UBS cut its
recommendation on the stock to “neutral” from “buy,” citing
valuation and “less positively skewed” near-term catalysts for
the company’s Xarelto blood-thinner.  Singulus rose 5.9 percent to 4.51 euros, the largest
advance since April 20. The maker of machines to produce Blu-ray
optical discs forecast a 33 percent increase in sales and
positive earnings this year after three years of losses.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Julie Cruz in  Frankfurt  at 
 jcruz6@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Andrew Rummer at   arummer@bloomberg.net  